        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="421"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d421">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/1154</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Third Secretary of Embassy in China</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sprouse</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="85" xml:id="d421fn85">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Ambassador in China in his despatch No. 580, August 18; received
                        September 10.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-12">August 12,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: War-time Regulations Governing Imports and Exports.</p>
                <p>During a call this afternoon on Mr. Rouse of the Chinese Maritime Customs
                    concerning another matter I took the opportunity of inquiring about the recently
                    announced regulations governing imports and exports. Mr. Rouse stated that to
                    all intents and purposes unlimited trade between Free China and the occupied
                    areas was now permitted under the regulations, that the Government recognized
                    the impossibility of preventing such trade, that Free China was greatly in need
                    of various articles produced in the occupied areas or in Japan and that the
                    Chinese Government sanctioned the trade as a means of obtaining <pb facs="0546"
                        n="536" xml:id="pg_536"/> the commodities desired and as a means of revenue
                    which would otherwise be lost because of smuggling. Mr. Rouse was of the opinion
                    that regardless of what articles were on the prohibited list, such as wood oil,
                    they would continue to be exported to the occupied areas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Philip D. Sprouse</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
